    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-12-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-12-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="148"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d148">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">463.00 R 29/181</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Unofficial Representative on the Reparation
                        Commission</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hill</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-12-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">7 December, 1925</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received December 16.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Supplementing my letter to the Department of
                    October 30th last concerning the question of Liberation Bonds, (share of the
                    cessionary States of the former Austro-Hungarian Monarchy), I have the honor to
                    enclose for the Department’s information, two copies of a communication! dated
                    December 5, 1925,<note n="17" xml:id="d148fn1">Not printed.</note> transmitting
                    a letter from the British Delegation to the Reparation Commission, dated
                    December 3, 1925,<note n="17" xml:id="d148fn2">Not printed.</note> in which it
                    is stated that the British Government takes the view that it would be preferable
                    not to call for the issue of the bonds in the present circumstances (F. S.
                    Document 60–a).</p>
                <p>A copy of these documents has been transmitted to the Embassy here for its
                    information.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ralph W. S. Hill</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
